(total: 35)<br>
<br>
-Shadow<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(50)">Uruk Soldier</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(154)">Orc Inquisitor</a> x4<br>
Ulaire Nertea x3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(46)">Uruk Rager</a> x4<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(56)">Uruk-hai Sword</a> x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(31)">Saruman&#39;s Ambition</a> x4<br>
Saruman Snows x4<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(20)">Breeding Pit</a><br>
Irresistible Shadow<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(135)">Desperate Defense of the Ring</a> x2<br>
(total: 35)<br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> We&#39;ve all had it happen to us.  Site 8 or 9... and the draw deck deals dry.  We&#39;ve hit the bottom rung and we&#39;re just pointing at people to take the hits that Frodo might&#39;ve dealt with, hoping they win to take the next few. It&#39;s a frustrating position to be in when your draw deck is gone.  Brought to you by myself and The Seem, that frustrating position can now reach an opponent with a 70 card deck by, hopefully, site 7.  This deck is there to create &quot;discardation frustration&quot;... <br>
<br>
Shadow...<br>
The shadow is very straight-forward.  In one turn, you have to cause as many discards as possible.  Go second.  These sites are built to help that happen.  <br>
Your Uruk Soldiers and Orc Inquisitors are there not to cause trouble, but to discard cards.  The Orc Inquisitor is pretty strong, but don&#39;t waste time trying to beef him up.  The moment he&#39;s stepped on the scene, he&#39;s done his job.  Same as the Uruk Soldier.  The Orc Inquisitor, is he only Sauron-Orc you have, so he&#39;s the one you&#39;re exerting when you pull out conditions.  Don&#39;t put him out without a condition following him.<br>
Uruk Soldiers are just there to cause discardation. Fellowship archery goes to the Soldiers, as well as your one Breeding pit (hope that you find it late...).  <br>
The Uruk Ragers are meant to win, though.  Saruman&#39;s Ambition, Saruman snows, Uruk-Hai Swords (another asset to discardation) are all there for your Ragers.  Don&#39;t waste any of them on the Soldiers.  Go straight for the Rager.  You&#39;re hoping that at the end of  skirmish the fellowship player discards more from the top of his draw deck... at the most, three!<br>
Ulaire Nertea is a commander to lead your Uruk Soldiers out of the discard pile and into discardation.  Don&#39;t waste his abilities, unless you&#39;re against a small fellowship (and in consequence, as small twilight pool.)  But the Goblin Runners just might be the thing to pump up a meager twilight pool...<br>
     Desperate Defense of the Ring is there to latch onto the Fellowship&#39;s big-beef fighters.  Just be sure to resist the temptation to put out two DDoRs on the table: the fellowship is very probably going to be able to Athelas or Sleep, Caradhras it off... pop down the other one when they do.<br>
     Irresistible Shadow is the card to limit the scope of the game. Once you deplete the draw deck, Frodo&#39;ll be taking burdens if he isn&#39;t overwhelmed.  When that happens often enough, it&#39;s over.<br>
<br>
Free Peoples...<br>
Discardation doesn&#39;t stop when it&#39;s your turn.  Arwen allows the Lorien elves to come out, pick up an Elven Bow and a White Arrows of Lorien... and the make the shadow player discard!  Discard, discard, discard.  Don&#39;t put an elven bow on Arwen, unless you&#39;re desperate.  When the Lorien Elves have done their job... chump-block. It saves Gimli the effort.<br>
Gimli is supposed to get out Greatest Kingdom of my People as quickly as you can (and just as swift, a dwarven axe).  That&#39;ll keep the discardation up at the opposition&#39;s doing... and when you beat up those orcs, discardation continues from the axe.  Gimli MUST win, so exert him, even, to do the job; Still Draws Breath will heal him.  Arwen is a help to Aragorn and Frodo, being the stalwart survivability.  Weapons for each of them keep the fellowship from being too weak or too important.<br>
As strong as the discardation gets, the sites help you through it.  Midgewater Moors... Pass of Caradhras... even Slopes of Amon Hen are there to make life easier on your Shadow efforts of discardation.  The others are there to help you.  Go second, and let them walk into your territories.<br>
<br>
Note:  Being only just for fun, this deck hasn&#39;t really been put together, or even really played.  The theory works well, and the deck should be able to play itself with only minor intervention and caution. If Lady Luck doesn&#39;t decide to screw you, things might be fun to watch... but, in the end, it probably won&#39;t be your opponent who&#39;s amused. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=21219"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=21219" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
